  "output": "## Test Coverage Analysis — jobsquare\n\n**Current state: zero test coverage.** No `tests/` directory, no pytest in `requirements.txt`, no CI test step (checked `.github/`). Every one of the ~75 functions across 8 modules is unexercised. Given the size, I'll prioritize by risk (pure logic first, since it's cheap to test and where regressions are most likely to slip in silently) and use `pytest` + `pytest-asyncio` + `respx` (for mocking `httpx`) as the harness.\n\n```\nrequirements-dev.txt   pytest>=8, pytest-asyncio>=0.24, respx>=0.21\ntests/\n  conftest.py\n  test_models.py\n  test_filters.py\n  test_store.py\n  test_notify.py\n  test_pipeline.py\n  test_agent.py\n  test_fetchers_parsers.py\n  test_fetchers_http.py\n```\n\n---\n\n### 1. `models.py` — highest-value gap, pure logic, zero tests\n\n`parse_posted_at` handles 3 input shapes (ms-epoch, s-epoch, ISO) plus malformed/empty input — this is exactly the kind of function that silently breaks a filter (`filters.py` cutoff logic depends on it) when a source changes format.\n\n**Gaps:** ms-vs-s epoch boundary, negative/garbage strings, `Job.key` stability, `content_hash` sensitivity to each of its 4 fields, `to_row()` dropping `raw`.\n\n```python\n# tests/test_models.py\nimport pytest\nfrom datetime import datetime, timezone\nfrom models import Job, parse_posted_at\n\n@pytest.mark.parametrize(\"value,expected\", [\n    (\"\", None),\n    (None, None),\n    (\"not-a-date\", None),\n    (\"1643241332430\", datetime(2022, 1, 26, 22, 55, 32, tzinfo=timezone.utc)),  # ms epoch\n    (\"1643241332\", datetime(2022, 1, 26, 22, 55, 32, tzinfo=timezone.utc)),      # s epoch\n    (\"2024-01-01T00:00:00Z\", datetime(2024, 1, 1, tzinfo=timezone.utc)),\n    (\"2024-01-01T00:00:00+05:00\", datetime(2023, 12, 31, 19, 0, tzinfo=timezone.utc)),\n    (\"2024-01-01T00:00:00\", datetime(2024, 1, 1, tzinfo=timezone.utc)),  # naive -> assume UTC\n])\ndef test_parse_posted_at(value, expected):\n    assert parse_posted_at(value) == expected\n\ndef test_parse_posted_at_epoch_boundary_off_by_one_digit():\n    # 999_999_999_999 (12 digits) must be treated as seconds, not ms\n    assert parse_posted_at(\"999999999999\").year > 2001\n\ndef test_job_key_is_stable_identity_not_content():\n    j1 = Job(source=\"lever\", company=\"acme\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"A\", url=\"u1\")\n    j2 = Job(source=\"lever\", company=\"acme\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"B\", url=\"u2\")\n    assert j1.key == j2.key  # same identity despite different content\n\ndef test_content_hash_changes_on_title_location_url_department_only():\n    base = Job(source=\"s\", company=\"c\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"T\", url=\"u\",\n               location=\"L\", department=\"D\")\n    import dataclasses\n    for field in (\"title\", \"location\", \"url\", \"department\"):\n        mutated = dataclasses.replace(base, **{field: \"changed\"})\n        assert mutated.content_hash != base.content_hash, field\n    # posted_at / salary_range are NOT part of the hash\n    same = dataclasses.replace(base, posted_at=\"2024-01-01\", salary_range=\"$1\")\n    assert same.content_hash == base.content_hash\n\ndef test_to_row_drops_raw_and_adds_key_and_hash():\n    j = Job(source=\"s\", company=\"c\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"T\", url=\"u\", raw={\"x\": 1})\n    row = j.to_row()\n    assert \"raw\" not in row\n    assert row[\"key\"] == j.key\n    assert row[\"content_hash\"] == j.content_hash\n```\n\n---\n\n### 2. `filters.py` — regex word-boundary edge cases untested\n\n**Gaps:** `include`/`exclude` interaction order (exclude wins when both match), word-boundary matching for punctuation-adjacent keywords (e.g. \"C++\", \"ML/AI\"), `cutoff` behavior on unparseable dates (must **keep**, not drop — that's a documented deliberate choice worth locking in), empty `rules` dict.\n\n```python\n# tests/test_filters.py\nimport pytest\nfrom datetime import datetime, timedelta, timezone\nfrom models import Job\nfrom filters import match, filter_jobs\n\ndef _job(title=\"Software Engineer\", dept=\"\", loc=\"Remote\", posted_at=\"\"):\n    return Job(source=\"s\", company=\"c\", external_id=\"1\", title=title,\n               url=\"u\", department=dept, location=loc, posted_at=posted_at)\n\ndef test_exclude_takes_priority_over_include():\n    j = _job(title=\"Senior Staff Manager Engineer\")\n    assert match(j, include=[\"engineer\"], exclude=[\"manager\"]) is False\n\ndef test_include_keyword_requires_word_boundary_not_substring():\n    j = _job(title=\"Engineering Intern\")\n    # \"engineer\" should NOT match \"Engineering\" as substring via \\b...\\b if plural/gerund differs\n    assert match(j, include=[\"engineer\"]) is False  # documents current behavior\n\ndef test_locations_filter_is_substring_case_insensitive():\n    j = _job(loc=\"San Francisco, CA\")\n    assert match(j, locations=[\"san francisco\"]) is True\n    assert match(j, locations=[\"nyc\"]) is False\n\ndef test_cutoff_keeps_jobs_with_unparseable_posted_at():\n    j = _job(posted_at=\"garbage\")\n    cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=1)\n    assert match(j, cutoff=cutoff) is True  # deliberate: don't nuke undated jobs\n\ndef test_cutoff_drops_jobs_older_than_cutoff():\n    old = _job(posted_at=(datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=30)).isoformat())\n    cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=7)\n    assert match(old, cutoff=cutoff) is False\n\ndef test_filter_jobs_empty_rules_returns_everything():\n    jobs = [_job(), _job(title=\"Other\")]\n    assert filter_jobs(jobs, {}) == jobs\n\ndef test_filter_jobs_max_age_days_accepts_float_string():\n    jobs = [_job(posted_at=datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat())]\n    assert len(filter_jobs(jobs, {\"max_age_days\": \"0.5\"})) == 1\n```\n\n---\n\n### 3. `store.py` — the dedup source of truth has no coverage at all\n\n**Gaps:** new vs. changed vs. unchanged classification, `content_hash`-only-field changes not tripping `changed` (e.g. `posted_at` alone changing shouldn't re-trigger since it's excluded from the hash — worth confirming that's intentional and tested), migration path (`salary_range` column added to legacy DB), `next_seq` concurrency claim, `added_since` string-comparison ordering.\n\n```python\n# tests/test_store.py\nimport pytest\nfrom models import Job\nfrom store import Store\n\n@pytest.fixture\ndef store(tmp_path):\n    with Store(tmp_path / \"test.db\") as s:\n        yield s\n\ndef _job(ext_id=\"1\", title=\"Engineer\", **kw):\n    return Job(source=\"greenhouse\", company=\"acme\", external_id=ext_id, title=title, url=\"u\", **kw)\n\ndef test_diff_classifies_new_jobs(store):\n    new, changed = store.diff([_job()])\n    assert len(new) == 1 and not changed\n    assert store.count() == 1\n\ndef test_diff_reruns_same_job_yields_no_new_no_changed(store):\n    store.diff([_job()])\n    new, changed = store.diff([_job()])\n    assert not new and not changed\n\ndef test_diff_detects_title_change_as_changed(store):\n    store.diff([_job(title=\"Engineer\")])\n    new, changed = store.diff([_job(title=\"Senior Engineer\")])\n    assert not new and len(changed) == 1\n\ndef test_diff_posted_at_only_change_is_not_flagged_changed(store):\n    # posted_at isn't part of content_hash by design (models.py) — confirm store honors that\n    store.diff([_job(posted_at=\"2024-01-01\")])\n    new, changed = store.diff([_job(posted_at=\"2024-06-01\")])\n    assert not new and not changed\n\ndef test_added_since_excludes_boundary_timestamp(store):\n    store.diff([_job()])\n    ts_after_insert = store.conn.execute(\"SELECT first_seen FROM jobs\").fetchone()[0]\n    assert store.added_since(ts_after_insert) == []  # strictly greater-than\n\ndef test_migrate_adds_salary_range_to_legacy_schema(tmp_path):\n    import sqlite3\n    path = tmp_path / \"legacy.db\"\n    conn = sqlite3.connect(path)\n    conn.executescript(\"\"\"\n        CREATE TABLE jobs (key TEXT PRIMARY KEY, source TEXT, company TEXT,\n          external_id TEXT, title TEXT, url TEXT, location TEXT, department TEXT,\n          employment_type TEXT, posted_at TEXT, content_hash TEXT,\n          first_seen TEXT, last_seen TEXT);\n        CREATE TABLE meta (k TEXT PRIMARY KEY, v TEXT);\n    \"\"\")\n    conn.commit(); conn.close()\n    with Store(path) as s:\n        cols = {r[\"name\"] for r in s.conn.execute(\"PRAGMA table_info(jobs)\")}\n        assert \"salary_range\" in cols\n\ndef test_next_seq_increments_and_persists(store):\n    assert store.next_seq(\"report_seq\") == 1\n    assert store.next_seq(\"report_seq\") == 2\n\ndef test_get_meta_missing_key_returns_none(store):\n    assert store.get_meta(\"nope\") is None\n```\n\n**Integration gap:** no test exercises real concurrent `next_seq` claims under `BEGIN IMMEDIATE` (the docstring explicitly calls out parallel-worker safety — [[jobsquare parallel worker collisions]] memory flags this class of bug has bitten the project before). Worth a threaded stress test:\n\n```python\ndef test_next_seq_serializes_concurrent_claims(tmp_path):\n    import threading\n    path = tmp_path / \"concurrent.db\"\n    results = []\n    def claim():\n        with Store(path) as s:\n            results.append(s.next_seq(\"k\"))\n    threads = [threading.Thread(target=claim) for _ in range(10)]\n    for t in threads: t.start()\n    for t in threads: t.join()\n    assert sorted(results) == list(range(1, 11))  # no duplicates, no gaps\n```\n\n---\n\n### 4. `notify.py` — env-gated notifiers, no mocking of `httpx.post`/`smtplib`\n\n**Gaps:** every notifier's \"activation\" gate (missing env var → silent no-op) is untested; `dispatch`'s per-notifier exception isolation (one notifier failing shouldn't block others) is the most important behavior in the file and is completely unverified; SMS body truncation at `limit`.\n\n```python\n# tests/test_notify.py\nimport pytest\nimport notify\nfrom models import Job\n\ndef _job(title=\"Engineer\"):\n    return Job(source=\"s\", company=\"c\", external_id=\"1\", title=title, url=\"u\")\n\ndef test_notify_slack_noop_without_env_var(monkeypatch, capsys):\n    monkeypatch.delenv(\"SLACK_WEBHOOK_URL\", raising=False)\n    notify.notify_slack([_job()], [])  # must not raise, must not call httpx\n\ndef test_notify_slack_posts_when_configured(monkeypatch):\n    monkeypatch.setenv(\"SLACK_WEBHOOK_URL\", \"https://hooks.example/x\")\n    calls = []\n    monkeypatch.setattr(notify.httpx, \"post\", lambda url, **kw: calls.append((url, kw)))\n    notify.notify_slack([_job()], [])\n    assert len(calls) == 1\n\ndef test_notify_slack_skips_post_when_no_jobs(monkeypatch):\n    monkeypatch.setenv(\"SLACK_WEBHOOK_URL\", \"https://hooks.example/x\")\n    monkeypatch.setattr(notify.httpx, \"post\", lambda *a, **k: pytest.fail(\"should not post\"))\n    notify.notify_slack([], [])\n\ndef test_sms_body_truncates_and_reports_overflow_count():\n    jobs = [_job(title=f\"Job {i}\") for i in range(12)]\n    body = notify._sms_body(jobs, [], limit=8)\n    assert \"+4 more\" in body\n    assert body.count(\"- Job\") == 8\n\ndef test_notify_sms_raises_on_bad_credentials(monkeypatch):\n    for k, v in {\"TWILIO_ACCOUNT_SID\": \"s\", \"TWILIO_AUTH_TOKEN\": \"t\",\n                 \"TWILIO_FROM\": \"+1\", \"TWILIO_TO\": \"+2\"}.items():\n        monkeypatch.setenv(k, v)\n    class FakeResp:\n        def raise_for_status(self): raise notify.httpx.HTTPStatusError(\n            \"401\", request=None, response=None)\n    monkeypatch.setattr(notify.httpx, \"post\", lambda *a, **k: FakeResp())\n    with pytest.raises(notify.httpx.HTTPStatusError):\n        notify.notify_sms([_job()], [])\n\ndef test_dispatch_isolates_notifier_failures(monkeypatch, capsys):\n    def boom(new, changed): raise RuntimeError(\"smtp down\")\n    monkeypatch.setattr(notify, \"NOTIFIERS\", [notify.notify_console, boom])\n    notify.dispatch([_job()], [])  # must not raise\n    assert \"notifier boom failed\" in capsys.readouterr().out\n```\n\n**Missing error-handling test entirely absent from the suite today:** `notify_email`'s SMTP auth branch (`if os.getenv(\"SMTP_USER\")`) and the case where `SMTP_USER` is set but `SMTP_PASS` isn't (would raise `KeyError` — worth asserting that's the actual, if ugly, current behavior so a future fix is deliberate).\n\n---\n\n### 5. `pipeline.py` — the orchestration seam, currently only reachable end-to-end via manual CLI runs\n\n**Gaps:** `dry_run` must not touch the store (currently unverified — a regression here would corrupt dedup state silently); config defaulting (`sources`, `filters`, `db`, `concurrency`); the return-value contract (`{\"matched\", \"new\", \"changed\"}`) that `agent.py`/mode files likely depend on.\n\n```python\n# tests/test_pipeline.py\nimport pytest\nfrom unittest.mock import AsyncMock, patch\nfrom models import Job\nimport pipeline\n\ndef test_load_config_applies_defaults(tmp_path):\n    cfg_path = tmp_path / \"empty.yaml\"\n    cfg_path.write_text(\"{}\")\n    cfg = pipeline.load_config(cfg_path)\n    assert cfg == {\"sources\": [], \"filters\": {}, \"db\": \"jobs.db\", \"concurrency\": 8}\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_dry_run_does_not_touch_store(tmp_path, monkeypatch):\n    cfg_path = tmp_path / \"c.yaml\"\n    cfg_path.write_text(f\"db: {tmp_path/'x.db'}\\nsources: []\\n\")\n    monkeypatch.setattr(pipeline, \"fetch_all\", AsyncMock(\n        return_value=[Job(source=\"s\", company=\"c\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"T\", url=\"u\")]))\n    result = await pipeline.run(cfg_path, dry_run=True)\n    assert result == {\"matched\": 1, \"new\": 0, \"changed\": 0}\n    assert not (tmp_path / \"x.db\").exists()  # store never opened\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_run_dispatches_notifications_for_new_jobs(tmp_path, monkeypatch):\n    cfg_path = tmp_path / \"c.yaml\"\n    cfg_path.write_text(f\"db: {tmp_path/'x.db'}\\nsources: []\\n\")\n    job = Job(source=\"s\", company=\"c\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"T\", url=\"u\")\n    monkeypatch.setattr(pipeline, \"fetch_all\", AsyncMock(return_value=[job]))\n    dispatched = []\n    monkeypatch.setattr(pipeline, \"dispatch\", lambda new, changed: dispatched.append((new, changed)))\n    result = await pipeline.run(cfg_path)\n    assert result[\"new\"] == 1\n    assert dispatched[0][0] == [job]\n```\n\n---\n\n### 6. `fetchers.py` — largest surface, split into (a) pure parsers and (b) network-bound fetchers\n\n#### 6a. Parsers — pure functions, cheap to test exhaustively, currently 0/~20 covered\n\nThe highest-risk pattern repeated across almost every parser is **defensive `.get()` chains over undocumented/positional payloads** (Google's `ds:1`, Apple's hydration blob, ByteDance's nested `city_info`). These degrade silently to empty fields on a real upstream change — exactly the failure mode described in memory [[Meta careers fetcher]] and [[Google careers fetch trap]]. Missing-key and malformed-payload cases are the real gap, not the happy path.\n\n```python\n# tests/test_fetchers_parsers.py\nfrom fetchers import (parse_greenhouse, parse_lever, parse_ashby, _lever_salary,\n                       _ashby_salary, parse_google, _extract_ds1, _ds1_posted_at,\n                       parse_deshaw, parse_apple, _apple_posted_at, _apple_hydration,\n                       parse_amazon, _amazon_posted_at, parse_bytedance, _bd_location,\n                       _balanced_json)\n\n# --- greenhouse --------------------------------------------------------\ndef test_parse_greenhouse_happy_path():\n    data = {\"jobs\": [{\"id\": 1, \"title\": \"SWE\", \"absolute_url\": \"u\",\n                       \"location\": {\"name\": \"NYC\"},\n                       \"departments\": [{\"name\": \"Eng\"}, {\"name\": \"Infra\"}],\n                       \"updated_at\": \"2024-01-01T00:00:00Z\"}]}\n    jobs = parse_greenhouse(\"acme\", data)\n    assert jobs[0].department == \"Eng, Infra\"\n\ndef test_parse_greenhouse_missing_location_and_departments():\n    data = {\"jobs\": [{\"id\": 1, \"title\": \"SWE\", \"absolute_url\": \"u\"}]}\n    jobs = parse_greenhouse(\"acme\", data)\n    assert jobs[0].location == \"\" and jobs[0].department == \"\"\n\ndef test_parse_greenhouse_empty_jobs_list():\n    assert parse_greenhouse(\"acme\", {\"jobs\": []}) == []\n\ndef test_parse_greenhouse_missing_jobs_key():\n    assert parse_greenhouse(\"acme\", {}) == []\n\ndef test_parse_greenhouse_missing_id_raises_keyerror():\n    # documents current behavior: a malformed record blows up the whole batch\n    import pytest\n    with pytest.raises(KeyError):\n        parse_greenhouse(\"acme\", {\"jobs\": [{\"title\": \"no id\"}]})\n\n# --- lever salary formatting -------------------------------------------\ndef test_lever_salary_range_formats_thousands_separator():\n    j = {\"salaryRange\": {\"min\": 120000, \"max\": 180000, \"currency\": \"USD\"}}\n    assert _lever_salary(j) == \"USD 120,000–180,000\"\n\ndef test_lever_salary_falls_back_to_description_plain():\n    j = {\"salaryDescriptionPlain\": \"DOE\"}\n    assert _lever_salary(j) == \"DOE\"\n\ndef test_lever_salary_missing_everything_returns_empty():\n    assert _lever_salary({}) == \"\"\n\ndef test_lever_salary_partial_range_falls_back():\n    j = {\"salaryRange\": {\"min\": 100000}}  # no max\n    assert _lever_salary(j) == \"\"\n\n# --- ashby: isListed filtering + posting-api vs page shapes ------------\ndef test_parse_ashby_skips_unlisted_jobs():\n    data = {\"jobs\": [{\"id\": \"1\", \"isListed\": False, \"title\": \"Hidden\"},\n                      {\"id\": \"2\", \"title\": \"Visible\"}]}\n    jobs = parse_ashby(\"acme\", data)\n    assert len(jobs) == 1 and jobs[0].external_id == \"2\"\n\ndef test_ashby_salary_prefers_tier_summary_over_scrapeable():\n    j = {\"compensation\": {\"compensationTierSummary\": \"L4\",\n                           \"scrapeableCompensationSalarySummary\": \"$100k\"}}\n    assert _ashby_salary(j) == \"L4\"\n\n# --- balanced json slicer (used by ashby hosted-page fallback) ---------\ndef test_balanced_json_handles_nested_braces_and_strings():\n    text = '{\"a\": {\"b\": \"c}}\"}, \"d\": 1}'\n    assert _balanced_json(text, 0) == text\n\ndef test_balanced_json_unterminated_returns_none():\n    assert _balanced_json('{\"a\": 1', 0) is None\n\ndef test_balanced_json_escaped_quote_inside_string():\n    text = r'{\"a\": \"esc\\\"aped\"}'\n    assert _balanced_json(text, 0) == text\n\n# --- google ds:1 positional blob, defensive indexing --------------------\ndef test_ds1_posted_at_prefers_create_over_update():\n    job = [None]*15\n    job[12] = [1700000000]\n    job[13] = [1800000000]\n    assert _ds1_posted_at(job).startswith(\"2023-11\")\n\ndef test_ds1_posted_at_short_array_returns_empty():\n    assert _ds1_posted_at([1, 2]) == \"\"\n\ndef test_extract_ds1_malformed_json_returns_empty_list():\n    html = \"key: 'ds:1', data:[not valid json], sideChannel\"\n    assert _extract_ds1(html) == []\n\ndef test_extract_ds1_missing_marker_returns_empty_list():\n    assert _extract_ds1(\"<html>nothing here</html>\") == []\n\ndef test_parse_google_skips_falsy_first_element():\n    assert parse_google(\"google\", [[None, \"title\"]]) == []\n\n# --- apple: nanosecond timestamp trimming --------------------------------\ndef test_apple_posted_at_trims_nanoseconds_to_microseconds():\n    result = _apple_posted_at(\"2024-01-01T00:00:03.812668311Z\")\n    assert result == \"2024-01-01T00:00:03.812668+00:00\"\n\ndef test_apple_posted_at_no_fractional_seconds():\n    assert _apple_posted_at(\"2024-01-01T00:00:03Z\") == \"2024-01-01T00:00:03+00:00\"\n\ndef test_apple_posted_at_empty_input():\n    assert _apple_posted_at(\"\") == \"\"\n\ndef test_apple_posted_at_garbage_input():\n    assert _apple_posted_at(\"not a date\") == \"\"\n\ndef test_apple_hydration_missing_marker_returns_none():\n    assert _apple_hydration(\"<html></html>\") is None\n\n# --- amazon date normalization -------------------------------------------\ndef test_amazon_posted_at_parses_us_format():\n    assert _amazon_posted_at(\"June 26, 2026\") == \"2026-06-26T00:00:00+00:00\"\n\ndef test_amazon_posted_at_unknown_month_returns_empty():\n    assert _amazon_posted_at(\"Frobtember 1, 2026\") == \"\"\n\ndef test_amazon_posted_at_malformed_string_returns_empty():\n    assert _amazon_posted_at(\"not-a-date\") == \"\"\n\ndef test_parse_amazon_id_falls_back_to_id_icims():\n    data = [{\"id_icims\": \"abc123\", \"title\": \"SWE\", \"job_path\": \"/x\"}]\n    jobs = parse_amazon(\"amazon\", data)\n    assert jobs[0].external_id == \"abc123\"\n\n# --- bytedance location chain walk ----------------------------------------\ndef test_bd_location_walks_parent_chain():\n    city = {\"en_name\": \"Seattle\", \"parent\": {\"en_name\": \"WA\", \"parent\": {\"en_name\": \"USA\"}}}\n    assert _bd_location(city) == \"Seattle, WA, USA\"\n\ndef test_bd_location_handles_none():\n    assert _bd_location(None) == \"\"\n\ndef test_bd_location_missing_names_in_middle_of_chain():\n    city = {\"parent\": {\"en_name\": \"USA\"}}  # city itself has no name\n    assert _bd_location(city) == \"USA\"\n```\n\n**Deduplication gap:** `parse_meta` dedupes on `jid` internally (`seen` set) but no other parser does, and none of that de-dup logic is tested anywhere — worth one test per parser that dedupes.\n\n```python\ndef test_parse_meta_dedupes_by_id():\n    from fetchers import parse_meta\n    results = [{\"id\": \"1\", \"title\": \"A\"}, {\"id\": \"1\", \"title\": \"A-dup\"}]\n    jobs = parse_meta(\"meta\", results)\n    assert len(jobs) == 1\n```\n\n#### 6b. Network-bound fetchers — completely untested, including retry/backoff and pagination termination\n\n**Gaps (highest risk first):**\n1. `_request`'s retry logic: retryable status codes (429/500/502/503/504) vs. non-retryable (404, 401), exhausting retries raises `RuntimeError`, transport errors retried.\n2. Pagination loop termination conditions — every `fetch_*` has a *different* stop condition (`fresh` empty, `total` reached, `max_pages` cap, `offset > 5000` safety cap for Workday). None are tested; an off-by-one here means either infinite-looking long fetches or silently truncated results.\n3. `fetch_ashby`'s 404-fallback branch (posting-api disabled → hosted page scrape) — the one fetcher with actual branching logic, entirely unexercised.\n4. `fetch_meta`'s token-scrape + `for (;;);` JSON prefix stripping + `errors` key surfacing a rotated `doc_id` — three failure-prone steps, zero tests.\n5. `fetch_all`'s per-source exception isolation (the same pattern as `notify.dispatch` — one source's exception must not kill the batch).\n\n```python\n# tests/test_fetchers_http.py\nimport pytest\nimport httpx\nimport respx\nfrom fetchers import _request, fetch_ashby, fetch_meta, fetch_all, fetch_workday\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\n@respx.mock\nasync def test_request_retries_on_503_then_succeeds():\n    route = respx.get(\"https://x.test/j\")\n    route.side_effect = [httpx.Response(503), httpx.Response(200, json={\"ok\": True})]\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient() as client:\n        r = await _request(client, \"https://x.test/j\", retries=3)\n    assert r.status_code == 200\n    assert route.call_count == 2\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\n@respx.mock\nasync def test_request_exhausts_retries_raises_runtime_error():\n    respx.get(\"https://x.test/j\").mock(return_value=httpx.Response(500))\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient() as client:\n        with pytest.raises(RuntimeError, match=\"failed to fetch\"):\n            await _request(client, \"https://x.test/j\", retries=2)\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\n@respx.mock\nasync def test_request_does_not_retry_on_404():\n    route = respx.get(\"https://x.test/j\").mock(return_value=httpx.Response(404))\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient() as client:\n        with pytest.raises(RuntimeError):\n            await _request(client, \"https://x.test/j\", retries=3)\n    assert route.call_count == 1  # 404 raises immediately via raise_for_status, no retry loop\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\n@respx.mock\nasync def test_fetch_ashby_falls_back_to_hosted_page_on_404():\n    respx.get(url__regex=r\"api\\.ashbyhq\\.com.*\").mock(return_value=httpx.Response(404))\n    html = 'window.__appData = {\"jobBoard\":{\"jobPostings\":[{\"id\":\"1\",\"title\":\"T\",\"isListed\":true}]}};'\n    respx.get(url__regex=r\"jobs\\.ashbyhq\\.com.*\").mock(return_value=httpx.Response(200, text=html))\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient() as client:\n        jobs = await fetch_ashby(client, {\"company\": \"acme\"})\n    assert len(jobs) == 1 and jobs[0].external_id == \"1\"\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\n@respx.mock\nasync def test_fetch_ashby_raises_when_appdata_missing():\n    respx.get(url__regex=r\"api\\.ashbyhq\\.com.*\").mock(return_value=httpx.Response(404))\n    respx.get(url__regex=r\"jobs\\.ashbyhq\\.com.*\").mock(return_value=httpx.Response(200, text=\"<html/>\"))\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient() as client:\n        with pytest.raises(RuntimeError, match=\"no posting-api\"):\n            await fetch_ashby(client, {\"company\": \"acme\"})\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\n@respx.mock\nasync def test_fetch_meta_strips_for_loop_prefix_and_parses():\n    page = '[\"LSD\",[],{\"token\":\"tok123\"}] \"__spin_r\":5 \"__spin_b\":\"b\" \"__spin_t\":9'\n    respx.get(\"https://www.metacareers.com/jobs\").mock(return_value=httpx.Response(200, text=page))\n    body = 'for (;;);{\"data\":{\"job_search_with_featured_jobs_v2\":{\"all_jobs\":[{\"id\":\"1\",\"title\":\"T\"}]}}}'\n    respx.post(\"https://www.metacareers.com/graphql\").mock(return_value=httpx.Response(200, text=body))\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient() as client:\n        jobs = await fetch_meta(client, {})\n    assert len(jobs) == 1\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\n@respx.mock\nasync def test_fetch_meta_raises_on_graphql_errors_payload():\n    respx.get(\"https://www.metacareers.com/jobs\").mock(return_value=httpx.Response(200, text=\"\"))\n    respx.post(\"https://www.metacareers.com/graphql\").mock(\n        return_value=httpx.Response(200, text='{\"errors\":[{\"message\":\"doc_id rotated\"}]}'))\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient() as client:\n        with pytest.raises(RuntimeError, match=\"doc_id rotated\"):\n            await fetch_meta(client, {})\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\n@respx.mock\nasync def test_fetch_all_isolates_source_failures(capsys):\n    respx.get(url__regex=r\"boards-api\\.greenhouse\\.io.*\").mock(side_effect=httpx.ConnectError(\"down\"))\n    respx.get(url__regex=r\"api\\.lever\\.co.*\").mock(\n        return_value=httpx.Response(200, json=[{\"id\": \"1\", \"text\": \"T\", \"hostedUrl\": \"u\"}]))\n    sources = [{\"ats\": \"greenhouse\", \"company\": \"dead\"}, {\"ats\": \"lever\", \"company\": \"alive\"}]\n    jobs = await fetch_all(sources, concurrency=2)\n    assert len(jobs) == 1  # lever succeeded despite greenhouse failing\n    assert \"dead\" in capsys.readouterr().out\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\n@respx.mock\nasync def test_fetch_workday_stops_at_offset_safety_cap():\n    # server never returns fewer postings than page_size and total is huge —\n    # must stop at the 5000-offset cap, not loop forever\n    respx.post(url__regex=r\".*\\/wday\\/cxs\\/.*\").mock(\n        return_value=httpx.Response(200, json={\n            \"jobPostings\": [{\"title\": \"T\", \"externalPath\": \"/x\"}] * 20,\n            \"total\": 999999}))\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient() as client:\n        jobs = await fetch_workday(client, {\"host\": \"h\", \"tenant\": \"t\", \"site\": \"s\", \"page_size\": 20})\n    assert len(jobs) <= 5020 // 20 * 20 + 20  # bounded, not infinite\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\n@respx.mock\nasync def test_fetch_source_unknown_ats_raises_valueerror():\n    from fetchers import fetch_source\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient() as client:\n        with pytest.raises(ValueError, match=\"unknown ATS\"):\n            await fetch_source(client, {\"ats\": \"not-a-real-ats\"})\n```\n\n**Note:** these need `respx` (a lightweight `httpx`-native mocking library) rather than hand-rolled `MockTransport`, since several fetchers make multiple sequential requests per call (pagination) and `respx` handles routing by URL pattern cleanly. The docstring in `fetchers.py` already states the client is injectable specifically \"so the parsing logic is unit-testable against mocked transports\" — the infrastructure was designed for this, it's just never been used.\n\n---\n\n### 7. `agent.py` — CLI + deterministic helpers, high-value pure logic buried in a big `main()`\n\n**Gaps:** `_normalize_ats` (ATS character normalization — directly affects generated PDFs a user sends to real employers, so a regression here is user-visible and embarrassing), `cmd_db_new`'s watermark/truncation/posted-days filtering logic (complex, multiple interacting flags, currently the most intricate untested function in the repo), `cmd_db_mark`'s ISO validation, argv parsing in `main()` (interactive vs. headless mode detection, flag-boundary splitting).\n\n```python\n# tests/test_agent.py\nimport pytest\nfrom agent import _normalize_ats, cmd_db_mark, cmd_db_new\nfrom store import Store\nfrom models import Job\n\n# --- ATS normalization ---------------------------------------------------\ndef test_normalize_ats_replaces_smart_quotes_and_dashes():\n    html = \"<p>It\\u2019s a \\u201Cgreat\\u201D role \\u2014 apply now</p>\"\n    out, counts = _normalize_ats(html)\n    assert \"\\u2019\" not in out and \"\\u201C\" not in out and \"\\u2014\" not in out\n    assert counts[\"em-dash\"] == 1\n\ndef test_normalize_ats_does_not_touch_style_or_script_blocks():\n    html = '<style>.x::after{content:\"\\u2014\"}</style><p>text \\u2014 here</p>'\n    out, counts = _normalize_ats(html)\n    assert '\"\\u2014\"' in out          # untouched inside <style>\n    assert counts[\"em-dash\"] == 1     # only the <p> occurrence counted\n\ndef test_normalize_ats_does_not_touch_tag_attributes():\n    html = '<a title=\"em\\u2014dash-in-attr\">text</a>'\n    out, counts = _normalize_ats(html)\n    assert 'title=\"em\\u2014dash-in-attr\"' in out  # attribute untouched\n    assert \"em-dash\" not in counts\n\ndef test_normalize_ats_no_special_chars_returns_empty_counts():\n    out, counts = _normalize_ats(\"<p>plain ascii text</p>\")\n    assert counts == {}\n\n# --- db-mark validation ---------------------------------------------------\ndef test_db_mark_rejects_non_iso_watermark(tmp_path, capsys):\n    cfg = tmp_path / \"s.yaml\"\n    cfg.write_text(f\"db: {tmp_path/'x.db'}\\n\")\n    rc = cmd_db_mark([\"not-a-timestamp\", \"-c\", str(cfg)])\n    assert rc == 2\n    assert \"not an ISO timestamp\" in capsys.readouterr().err\n\ndef test_db_mark_requires_watermark_or_now(tmp_path, capsys):\n    cfg = tmp_path / \"s.yaml\"\n    cfg.write_text(f\"db: {tmp_path/'x.db'}\\n\")\n    rc = cmd_db_mark([\"-c\", str(cfg)])\n    assert rc == 2\n\n# --- db-new filtering/truncation ------------------------------------------\ndef test_db_new_first_run_uses_since_days_window(tmp_path, capsys):\n    cfg = tmp_path / \"s.yaml\"\n    db_path = tmp_path / \"x.db\"\n    cfg.write_text(f\"db: {db_path}\\n\")\n    with Store(db_path) as s:\n        s.diff([Job(source=\"g\", company=\"c\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"T\", url=\"u\")])\n    import json\n    cmd_db_new([\"-c\", str(cfg)])\n    out = json.loads(capsys.readouterr().out)\n    assert out[\"first_run\"] is True\n    assert out[\"count\"] == 1\n\ndef test_db_new_dated_only_drops_undated_rows(tmp_path, capsys):\n    cfg = tmp_path / \"s.yaml\"\n    db_path = tmp_path / \"x.db\"\n    cfg.write_text(f\"db: {db_path}\\n\")\n    with Store(db_path) as s:\n        s.diff([Job(source=\"g\", company=\"c\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"Undated\", url=\"u\"),\n                Job(source=\"g\", company=\"c\", external_id=\"2\", title=\"Dated\", url=\"u\",\n                    posted_at=\"2024-01-01T00:00:00Z\")])\n    import json\n    cmd_db_new([\"-c\", str(cfg), \"--posted-days\", \"3650\", \"--dated-only\"])\n    out = json.loads(capsys.readouterr().out)\n    assert out[\"undated_dropped\"] == 1\n    assert out[\"count\"] == 1\n\ndef test_db_new_truncates_at_group_boundary_not_mid_group(tmp_path, capsys):\n    # two jobs inserted in the SAME store.diff() call share one first_seen\n    # timestamp; --limit 1 must not silently drop one of them mid-group\n    cfg = tmp_path / \"s.yaml\"\n    db_path = tmp_path / \"x.db\"\n    cfg.write_text(f\"db: {db_path}\\n\")\n    with Store(db_path) as s:\n        s.diff([Job(source=\"g\", company=\"c\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"A\", url=\"u\"),\n                Job(source=\"g\", company=\"c\", external_id=\"2\", title=\"B\", url=\"u\")])\n    import json\n    cmd_db_new([\"-c\", str(cfg), \"--limit\", \"1\"])\n    out = json.loads(capsys.readouterr().out)\n    # first group (2 jobs) exceeds limit=1 but jobs list started empty, so the\n    # whole group is kept whole per the \"jobs and ... > limit\" guard\n    assert out[\"count\"] == 2 or out[\"count\"] == 0  # pin down actual behavior\n```\n\nThat last test is intentionally phrased to *discover* the real boundary behavior (the `if jobs and len(jobs) + len(g) > a.limit` guard means the very first group is always admitted in full, regardless of `--limit`) — worth running it once to see which branch fires, then hard-asserting on the correct value rather than an `or`.\n\n**Missing error-handling tests, `agent.py`:**\n- `cmd_pdf_render` with a nonexistent input file (returns 2) — untested.\n- `cmd_pdf_render` when Chrome renders but produces a non-PDF (corrupt/empty) output — the `data.startswith(b\"%PDF\")` guard is untested.\n- `_chrome_bin()` when no Chrome is found anywhere (`sys.exit`) — untested.\n- `main()`'s flag-boundary splitting (`mode_words` vs `extra`) for inputs like `agent.py scan --posted-days 3` — untested, and it's the exact function most likely to silently swallow user CLI args wrong.\n\n---\n\n### 8. Integration test gaps (cross-module, currently nothing exercises these end-to-end)\n\n1. **Full pipeline round-trip**: `pipeline.run()` against a real (tmp) SQLite `Store`, mocked `fetch_all`, asserting jobs flow through filter → dedup → notify correctly and the DB ends up in the expected state. (Partially covered above but worth one true end-to-end test with 3 pipeline runs simulating \"first seen\" → \"unchanged\" → \"changed\".)\n2. **agent.py `db-new` → `db-mark` cycle**: scan, dump, mark, scan again — confirming the watermark logic never re-surfaces or skips a row. This is the core correctness property of the whole scan feature and has no test.\n3. **A real ATS parser wired through `fetch_source` → `filter_jobs` → `Store.diff`**: e.g. a Greenhouse fixture payload through the entire pipeline, verifying `Job.key`/`content_hash` produced by the parser survive round-trip through SQLite unchanged.\n4. **`sources.yaml` itself**: no test validates every entry has a `parse_*`/`fetch_*` counterpart in `FETCHERS`, or that required per-ATS config keys (e.g. Workday's `host`/`tenant`/`site`) are present for every Workday-typed entry — a config typo currently only surfaces at 3am during a scheduled run.\n\n```python\n# tests/test_integration_config.py\nimport yaml\nfrom fetchers import FETCHERS\n\ndef test_sources_yaml_every_ats_is_registered():\n    cfg = yaml.safe_load(open(\"sources.yaml\"))\n    unknown = {s[\"ats\"] for s in cfg[\"sources\"]} - set(FETCHERS)\n    assert not unknown, f\"sources.yaml references unregistered ATS types: {unknown}\"\n\ndef test_workday_sources_have_required_keys():\n    cfg = yaml.safe_load(open(\"sources.yaml\"))\n    for s in cfg[\"sources\"]:\n        if s[\"ats\"] == \"workday\":\n            missing = {\"host\", \"tenant\", \"site\"} - s.keys()\n            assert not missing, f\"{s.get('company')}: missing {missing}\"\n```\n\n---\n\n### Priority order if I were implementing this\n\n1. `models.py` + `filters.py` — pure, fast, highest bug-catching value per line.\n2. `store.py` diff/migration — protects the dedup invariant the whole system depends on.\n3. `fetchers.py` parsers (6a) — parametrized over all ~20, focus on missing-key/malformed-payload defensiveness since that's the recurring real-world failure mode per your memory notes on Meta/Google/ByteDance fetchers breaking silently.\n4. `agent.py` `_normalize_ats` + `cmd_db_new` — user-visible (PDF output) and logically dense (watermark/truncation), respectively.\n5. `notify.py` `dispatch` isolation + `fetchers.py` `fetch_all`/`_request` retry logic — both implement the same \"one failure shouldn't kill the batch\" pattern; test them together to also confirm they're implemented consistently between modules.\n6. Network-bound fetchers (6b) and integration tests — most effort per test, do last.\n",
